      <!-- Research-->
      <div class="row research">

         <div class="three columns header-col">
            <h1><span>Research</span></h1>
         </div>

         <div class="nine columns main-col">

            <div class="row item">

               <div class="twelve columns">

                  <h3>Interests</h3>
<!--                  <p class="info">Master in Graphic Design <span>&bull;</span> <em class="date">April 2007</em></p> -->

                  <p>
                    My main interest consists in the understanding of the subcritical transition between the laminar and turbulent flow states.
                    I am interested in an approach to transition based on dynamical systems, where the so called
                    <b>edge states</b> are studied.
                    The edge state is an unstable state living on the boundary that separates the basins of attraction
                    for the laminar and turbulent flow states. 
                    I am particularly interested into boundary-layer configurations,
                     which involve an additional degree of complexity due to the spatial development of the flow.
                     To study the complex dynamics we perform large-scale direct numerical simulations using a pseudo-spectral code combined with low-order models.
                     I am also interested in hydrodynamics stability of jets, focusing on complex jets, and to some extent in bioflows.
                  </p>


                  <h3>Publications</h3>
		  <!--                  <p class="info">Master in Graphic Design <span>&bull;</span> <em class="date">April 2007</em></p> -->

		  <p>4. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, Y. Duguet & D. S. Henningson.
                    A model for the collapse of the edge when two transition routes compete. Under review in <i>Phys. Rev. E</i> <a href=https://arxiv.org/pdf/2005.11047.pdf>(arXiv)</a> 
                  </p>
		  
		  <p>3. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, Y. Duguet, P. Schlatter & D. S. Henningson (2020).
                    The edge as a Lagrangian Coherent Structure in a high-dimensional state space. Accepted in <i>Phys. Rev. Research </i> <a href=https://arxiv.org/pdf/2004.00887.pdf>(arXiv)</a> 
                  </p>
		  
                  <p>2. C. Vavaliaris, <b>M. Beneitez</b> & D. S. Henningson (2020).
                    Optimal perturbations and transition energy thresholds in boundary layer shear flows. <i>Phys. Rev. Fluids</i> <b>5</b>, 062401(R)   <a href=https://journals.aps.org/prfluids/pdf/10.1103/PhysRevFluids.5.062401>(PDF)</a> 
                  </p>

                  <p>1. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, Y. Duguet, P. Schlatter & D. S. Henningson (2019).
                    Edge tracking in spatially developing boundary layer flows.  <i>J. Fluid Mech.</i> <b>881</b>, 164-181 <a href=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/0E334783C22461322D491A25FA3DC7B2/S0022112019007638a.pdf/edge_tracking_in_spatially_developing_boundary_layer_flows.pdf>(PDF)</a> 
                  </p>


                  <h3>Conference Contributions</h3>
		  <!--                  <p class="info">Master in Graphic Design <span>&bull;</span> <em class="date">April 2007</em></p> -->

		  <p>
                    5.  Y. Duguet, <b>M. Beneitez</b>, P. Schlatter & D. S. Henningson. What can we learn from the Edge about bypass transition. ETC17, Torino, Italy Sep. 2019
                  </p>
		  
		  <p>
                    4.  C. Vavaliaris, <b>M. Beneitez</b> & D. S. Henningson. Optimal initial perturbations and the minimal seed of Blasius boundary-layer flow. ETC17, Torino, Italy Sep. 2019
                  </p>
		  
                  <p>
                    3. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, Y. Duguet, P. Schlatter & D. S. Henningson. What can we learn from the Edge about bypass transition. IUTAM transition 2019, London, U.K. Sep. 2019
                  </p>

		  <p>
                    2. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, Y. Duguet, P. Schlatter & D. S. Henningson. The edge for boundary layer
                    flows. Euromech Colloquium 598: Coherent structures in wall-bounded turbulence: new directions
                    in a classical problem, London, U.K. Aug. 2018
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    1. <b>M. Beneitez</b>, M. Rubio-Rubio & A. Sevilla. On the
                    steady structure of vertical slender liquid jets with non-uniform outlet velocity profiles.
                     11th European Fluid Mechanics Conference, Seville, Spain. Sept. 2016
                  </p>

